c works that helped to transform Canada from wilderness to a modern country. For the first time, a single volume describes Canadian history in terms of its public works. Each chapter includes highlights and examples of standard practice, along with a wealth of illustrations.Members of the Canadian Public Works Association have sponsored this volume in recognition of the accomplishments of their predecessors and the achievements of their profession.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPublic workszCanadaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Letty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndreae, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArtibise, Alan F. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldwin, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBall, Norman R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFram, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurst, William D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinteau, Paul-André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNally, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtter, A. A. den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPassfield, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoos, Arnold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimonton, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is 